{id:1151,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Regression Testing in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the test automation pyramid?",options:["A. A hierarchy showing more unit tests at the base fewer UI tests at the top","B. A pyramid showing more manual tests at the base","C. A model for organizing the product backlog","D. A risk assessment framework"],answer:0,explanation:"The test automation pyramid recommends many unit tests at the base, fewer integration tests in the middle, and fewest UI tests at the top."},
{id:1152,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Agile Test Strategy",difficulty:"medium",question:"In Agile, what does test early and test often mean?",options:["A. Tests should only be written before development","B. Testing activities should begin as early as possible and continue throughout development","C. All features must be tested every day","D. Testers should work before developers in each sprint"],answer:1,explanation:"Test early and often means starting testing from the first sprint and running tests continuously throughout development."},
{id:1153,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Test Independence",difficulty:"easy",question:"Why might a team use a dedicated tester separate from the developer writing the code?",options:["A. To slow down development","B. To provide an independent perspective less biased by implementation knowledge","C. Because developers cannot write tests","D. To satisfy legal requirements"],answer:1,explanation:"Independent testers are less familiar with implementation details, making them more likely to find unexpected defects."},
{id:1154,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Testing Quadrants",difficulty:"easy",question:"Brian Marick's Testing Quadrants model was designed to help teams:",options:["A. Prioritize defect fixing","B. Plan a balanced set of testing activities across different perspectives","C. Estimate sprint velocity","D. Organize the product backlog"],answer:1,explanation:"The Testing Quadrants help teams plan a comprehensive and balanced set of testing activities."},
{id:1155,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Whole-Team Approach",difficulty:"hard",question:"In Agile, what is the purpose of a definition of done for testing?",options:["A. To list all test cases that must be written","B. To define shared criteria the team uses to determine when a story is truly complete","C. To specify the number of tests per story","D. To assign testing tasks to team members"],answer:1,explanation:"The Definition of Done includes testing criteria — the team shares a common understanding of what done means."},
{id:1156,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Tester Role in Agile",difficulty:"hard",question:"A tester notices many stories have unclear acceptance criteria. The BEST action is to:",options:["A. Test the stories without acceptance criteria","B. Raise the issue with the Product Owner and team to improve acceptance criteria before development","C. Skip testing those stories","D. Write the acceptance criteria alone after testing"],answer:1,explanation:"Testers should proactively engage with POs to clarify acceptance criteria before development starts — preventing defects."},
{id:1157,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Test Levels in Agile",difficulty:"hard",question:"Integration testing in Agile MOST typically focuses on:",options:["A. Testing the complete system against all requirements","B. Verifying that components and services work correctly together","C. Testing individual functions in isolation","D. Performing user acceptance testing"],answer:1,explanation:"Integration testing verifies that components interact correctly — APIs, services, and modules working together."},
{id:1158,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Testing Quadrants",difficulty:"hard",question:"Q2 tests in the Agile Testing Quadrants are BEST described as:",options:["A. Tests that critique the product from a technical perspective","B. Business-facing tests that support the team like functional and story tests","C. Tests that find performance bottlenecks","D. Tests that check security vulnerabilities"],answer:1,explanation:"Q2 sits in the business-facing support-the-team quadrant — functional tests, story tests, and prototypes."},
{id:1159,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Regression Testing in Agile",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team has 500 automated regression tests running in 3 minutes. A new sprint adds 50 tests. Which concern is MOST relevant?",options:["A. The tests are too fast","B. Test suite growth may eventually slow the feedback loop if not managed","C. 550 tests are too many","D. New tests should replace old ones"],answer:1,explanation:"Unmanaged growth of the regression suite can eventually slow feedback — teams must keep the suite fast and relevant."},
{id:1160,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Test Independence",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team debates whether to use developers or external testers for acceptance testing. The PRIMARY advantage of external testers is:",options:["A. They are cheaper","B. They bring unbiased perspective and represent real user viewpoints","C. They have more technical skills","D. They complete testing faster"],answer:1,explanation:"External testers bring independent perspective and may better represent user viewpoints, reducing confirmation bias."},
{id:1161,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Whole-Team Approach",difficulty:"extreme",question:"In a mature Agile team, quality is BEST maintained by:",options:["A. A dedicated QA gate at the end of each sprint","B. Built-in quality practices throughout development including TDD peer reviews and continuous testing","C. External audits after each release","D. The Scrum Master reviewing all code"],answer:1,explanation:"Mature Agile teams build quality in continuously through TDD, code reviews, automated testing, and collaboration."},
{id:1162,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Tester Role in Agile",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile tester is asked to mentor developers on writing better unit tests. This is an example of:",options:["A. Role confusion","B. The whole team quality approach — testers contributing testing expertise to all team members","C. Overstepping the tester responsibilities","D. Replacing the developer role"],answer:1,explanation:"Testers coaching developers on test quality is a healthy whole-team quality practice in Agile."},
{id:1163,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Test Levels in Agile",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team skips system testing and relies only on unit and integration tests. What is the MAIN risk?",options:["A. Unit tests will break","B. End-to-end system behavior and interactions may not be verified","C. The sprint will be cancelled","D. The Product Owner will reject the increment"],answer:1,explanation:"System testing verifies the complete system behavior — skipping it risks missing defects that only emerge at the system level."},
{id:1164,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Testing Quadrants",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team only uses Q1 tests (unit tests). Which types of testing risk are they taking?",options:["A. No risk — unit tests cover everything","B. Missing business validation exploratory performance and security testing from Q2 Q3 and Q4","C. Tests will run too fast","D. The backlog will grow"],answer:1,explanation:"Relying only on Q1 leaves the team without business validation, exploratory, UAT, performance, and security coverage."},
{id:1165,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Whole-Team Approach",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following BEST demonstrates the whole team approach to quality?",options:["A. Only the test team reviews the Definition of Done","B. All team members including developers and PO contribute to defining and meeting quality standards","C. Quality is reviewed by an external team at the end of each sprint","D. Developers hand off work to testers after completing all stories"],answer:1,explanation:"Whole team quality means all team members — developers, testers, PO — share ownership of quality standards."},
{id:1166,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Tester Role in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"In Agile what is the tester's role during sprint planning?",options:["A. To approve all stories before they enter the sprint","B. To provide testing estimates and identify testability issues for planned stories","C. To create the sprint backlog","D. To manage the product backlog priority"],answer:1,explanation:"Testers participate in sprint planning by providing testing effort estimates and identifying any testability concerns."},
{id:1167,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Test Levels in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is component testing in Agile?",options:["A. Testing the complete system","B. Testing individual software components in isolation or integration","C. Testing user interfaces only","D. Testing database queries"],answer:1,explanation:"Component testing verifies individual software components or modules work correctly, often using stubs and drivers."},
{id:1168,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Agile Test Strategy",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is a test approach in Agile?",options:["A. A detailed test plan for the entire project","B. How the team intends to test the product — techniques tools and levels used","C. A list of all test cases","D. The Definition of Done for testing"],answer:1,explanation:"A test approach describes how the team will test — the techniques, tools, levels, and focus areas they will use."},
{id:1169,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Regression Testing in Agile",difficulty:"easy",question:"Why is regression testing important in Agile?",options:["A. To test new features only","B. To ensure changes do not break previously working functionality","C. To replace all manual testing","D. To improve team velocity"],answer:1,explanation:"Regression testing ensures that new changes don't break existing functionality — critical in Agile's rapid iteration environment."},
{id:1170,chapter:"Fundamental Aspects of Agile Testing",topic:"Test Independence",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the MAIN benefit of having testers review user stories before development begins?",options:["A. To slow down the development team","B. To identify ambiguities and missing acceptance criteria early reducing defects","C. To assign work to developers","D. To replace the Product Owner"],answer:1,explanation:"Tester review of stories before development catches ambiguity early — preventing defects from being built in."},
{id:1171,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test-Driven Development",difficulty:"easy",question:"In TDD, what is the correct sequence of steps?",options:["A. Write code, write test, refactor","B. Write failing test, write code to pass, refactor","C. Refactor, write test, write code","D. Write test, refactor, write code"],answer:1,explanation:"TDD follows Red-Green-Refactor: write a failing test, write minimal code to pass it, then refactor."},
{id:1172,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test-Driven Development",difficulty:"easy",question:"What type of tests does TDD primarily produce?",options:["A. Performance tests","B. Unit tests","C. Acceptance tests","D. End-to-end tests"],answer:1,explanation:"TDD primarily produces unit tests — small, focused tests written before the code they verify."},
{id:1173,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"ATDD",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does ATDD stand for?",options:["A. Automated Test-Driven Design","B. Acceptance Test-Driven Development","C. Advanced Test Design Discipline","D. Agile Test Delivery Directive"],answer:1,explanation:"ATDD stands for Acceptance Test-Driven Development — acceptance tests are written before coding begins."},
{id:1174,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"ATDD",difficulty:"medium",question:"In ATDD, acceptance tests are typically written:",options:["A. After the feature is complete","B. Before development begins collaboratively by PO developer and tester","C. Only by the tester","D. Only by the Product Owner"],answer:1,explanation:"ATDD uses acceptance tests written collaboratively (three amigos) before development to guide implementation."},
{id:1175,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"BDD",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does BDD stand for?",options:["A. Bug-Driven Development","B. Behavior-Driven Development","C. Business-Driven Design","D. Baseline-Driven Delivery"],answer:1,explanation:"BDD stands for Behavior-Driven Development — scenarios are defined in a business-readable language like Gherkin."},
{id:1176,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"BDD",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which format is commonly used to write BDD scenarios?",options:["A. XML","B. Given-When-Then","C. UML sequence diagrams","D. JSON"],answer:1,explanation:"BDD scenarios use the Given-When-Then format to describe system behavior in a readable way."},
{id:1177,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"BDD",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the PRIMARY benefit of BDD?",options:["A. It eliminates the need for unit tests","B. It creates a shared understanding of behavior between business and technical team members","C. It speeds up test execution","D. It replaces manual testing"],answer:1,explanation:"BDD bridges the communication gap between business and technical stakeholders by expressing behavior in plain language."},
{id:1178,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Exploratory Testing",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is exploratory testing?",options:["A. Testing based on a predefined test script","B. Simultaneous learning test design and test execution","C. Automated regression testing","D. Testing only new features"],answer:1,explanation:"Exploratory testing combines learning about the system, designing tests, and executing them simultaneously."},
{id:1179,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Exploratory Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"Why is exploratory testing valuable in Agile?",options:["A. It replaces all scripted testing","B. It finds defects that scripted tests miss and provides rapid feedback on new features","C. It eliminates the need for automation","D. It satisfies compliance requirements"],answer:1,explanation:"Exploratory testing uncovers unexpected defects and provides fast, flexible coverage of new features."},
{id:1180,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"User Story Testing",difficulty:"easy",question:"What are acceptance criteria in a user story?",options:["A. Technical implementation details","B. Conditions that must be met for the story to be accepted as done","C. Performance benchmarks","D. Test automation scripts"],answer:1,explanation:"Acceptance criteria define the conditions a story must satisfy to be accepted by the Product Owner."},
{id:1181,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"User Story Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which user story format is MOST commonly used in Agile?",options:["A. As a [role] I want [feature] so that [benefit]","B. When [event] happens then [outcome]","C. Given [context] when [action] then [result]","D. The system shall [do something]"],answer:0,explanation:"The standard user story format captures who wants what and why: As a role I want feature so that benefit."},
{id:1182,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test Automation in Agile",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the MAIN advantage of test automation in Agile?",options:["A. It replaces the need for testers","B. It enables fast repeatable regression testing to support frequent releases","C. It generates requirements automatically","D. It eliminates all manual testing"],answer:1,explanation:"Automation enables fast regression testing, supporting Agile's need for rapid, frequent releases."},
{id:1183,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test Automation in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which type of test should form the LARGEST portion of the test automation pyramid?",options:["A. UI end-to-end tests","B. Unit tests","C. Integration tests","D. Performance tests"],answer:1,explanation:"The test automation pyramid recommends the largest volume of fast, reliable unit tests at the base."},
{id:1184,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"CI/CD and Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is continuous integration in the context of Agile testing?",options:["A. Testing all features once per release","B. Automatically building and testing code every time changes are committed","C. Integrating test plans with the backlog","D. Running tests in the cloud"],answer:1,explanation:"CI automatically builds and tests code on every commit, providing rapid feedback on code quality."},
{id:1185,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"CI/CD and Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the role of automated tests in a CI/CD pipeline?",options:["A. To replace manual acceptance testing","B. To provide fast quality gates that catch defects before they reach production","C. To document test results for auditors","D. To replace all human testing"],answer:1,explanation:"Automated tests in CI/CD pipelines act as quality gates, catching defects early before they propagate downstream."},
{id:1186,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test-Driven Development",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the red phase in TDD Red-Green-Refactor cycle?",options:["A. Writing code that has errors","B. Writing and running a failing test","C. Running all tests and finding failures","D. Deploying broken code"],answer:1,explanation:"The red phase is writing a test that currently fails — it defines the behavior that needs to be implemented."},
{id:1187,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"ATDD",difficulty:"medium",question:"How does ATDD differ from TDD?",options:["A. ATDD uses acceptance criteria to drive development; TDD uses unit tests","B. ATDD is only for performance testing; TDD is for functional testing","C. ATDD is manual; TDD is automated","D. ATDD and TDD are the same practice"],answer:0,explanation:"ATDD drives development from high-level acceptance criteria, while TDD drives it from low-level unit tests."},
{id:1188,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"BDD",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which of the following is a BDD framework commonly used in software testing?",options:["A. JUnit","B. Cucumber","C. Selenium","D. Jenkins"],answer:1,explanation:"Cucumber is a popular BDD framework that uses Gherkin Given-When-Then syntax for feature files."},
{id:1189,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Exploratory Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is a time-boxed exploratory testing session called?",options:["A. Sprint","B. Test charter","C. Session-based test management","D. Spike"],answer:2,explanation:"Session-based test management organizes exploratory testing into time-boxed sessions with defined charters and debrief."},
{id:1190,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"User Story Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which of the following BEST describes INVEST criteria for user stories?",options:["A. Independent Negotiable Valuable Estimable Small Testable","B. Integrated Notable Validated Expandable Scalable Tested","C. Important Novel Verified Essential Structured Timed","D. Individual New Vetted Extended Safe Tracked"],answer:0,explanation:"INVEST: Independent, Negotiable, Valuable, Estimable, Small, Testable — criteria for well-formed user stories."},
{id:1191,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test Automation in Agile",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team finds their UI automation tests are flaky and slow. Which solution BEST aligns with the test automation pyramid?",options:["A. Add more UI tests to improve coverage","B. Replace flaky UI tests with lower-level unit and API tests where possible","C. Remove all automation and use only manual testing","D. Run UI tests less frequently"],answer:1,explanation:"The pyramid recommends fewer targeted UI tests — moving coverage to unit and API tests improves speed and reliability."},
{id:1192,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"CI/CD and Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is a deployment pipeline?",options:["A. A Kanban column for deployment tasks","B. An automated process that moves code from commit through testing stages to production","C. A document describing the release process","D. A tool for managing the product backlog"],answer:1,explanation:"A deployment pipeline automates the steps from code commit through build, test, and staging to production deployment."},
{id:1193,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test-Driven Development",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is a key benefit of TDD beyond test coverage?",options:["A. Faster code writing speed","B. Improved design — TDD forces modular testable code by design","C. Elimination of code reviews","D. Reduced documentation needs"],answer:1,explanation:"TDD improves code design by requiring developers to write testable, loosely coupled code from the start."},
{id:1194,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"ATDD",difficulty:"hard",question:"In ATDD, what happens when an acceptance test fails after implementation?",options:["A. The story is cancelled","B. The team debugs and fixes the implementation until the acceptance test passes","C. The acceptance criterion is removed","D. A new sprint is started"],answer:1,explanation:"A failing acceptance test indicates the implementation doesn't yet meet the agreed behavior — the team fixes it."},
{id:1195,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"BDD",difficulty:"hard",question:"In BDD, the Given-When-Then format serves to:",options:["A. Document database schemas","B. Define preconditions actions and expected outcomes in a readable scenario","C. Describe system architecture","D. Create sprint backlog items"],answer:1,explanation:"Given-When-Then describes context, action, and expected outcome clearly for both business and technical stakeholders."},
{id:1196,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Exploratory Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is a test charter in exploratory testing?",options:["A. The formal test plan document","B. A brief mission statement that guides an exploratory test session","C. A list of all test cases to execute","D. A performance benchmark"],answer:1,explanation:"A test charter defines the scope and mission of an exploratory session: what to explore, with which approach."},
{id:1197,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"User Story Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"When a user story has poor acceptance criteria, what is the MOST likely consequence?",options:["A. Faster development","B. Mismatched expectations between developer and stakeholder leading to rework","C. Better test coverage","D. Reduced defect count"],answer:1,explanation:"Vague acceptance criteria lead to different interpretations, causing rework when the feature doesn't match expectations."},
{id:1198,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test Automation in Agile",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team's automated test suite takes 45 minutes to run blocking CI feedback. The MOST appropriate action is to:",options:["A. Remove automation entirely","B. Optimize and parallelize tests; split into fast smoke and slower full suites","C. Only run tests at release time","D. Replace all tests with manual testing"],answer:1,explanation:"Parallelizing tests and splitting into fast/slow tiers maintains rapid feedback while keeping full coverage."},
{id:1199,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"CI/CD and Testing",difficulty:"extreme",question:"In a fully automated CD pipeline, which practice ensures production deployments are safe?",options:["A. Manual approval at every stage","B. Progressive delivery with feature flags canary releases and automated rollback","C. Testing only in staging","D. Deploying only once per quarter"],answer:1,explanation:"Progressive delivery techniques like canary releases and feature flags with automated rollback make CD safe."},
{id:1200,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"BDD",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team writes BDD scenarios that are too implementation-specific. What is the PRIMARY problem?",options:["A. Scenarios are too long","B. Scenarios are brittle and break with every code change rather than describing stable behavior","C. Business stakeholders write scenarios","D. Scenarios use Given-When-Then format"],answer:1,explanation:"Implementation-specific scenarios become brittle — they break when implementation changes even if behavior is correct."},
{id:1201,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test-Driven Development",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A developer writes tests only after completing features to get code coverage metrics. This is MOST problematic because:",options:["A. It increases test count unnecessarily","B. It defeats TDD purpose — tests no longer drive design and coverage may not reflect meaningful validation","C. Tests written after code are always wrong","D. It violates the Agile Manifesto"],answer:1,explanation:"Writing tests purely for coverage after the fact misses TDD's design benefits and may confirm wrong behavior."},
{id:1202,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"ATDD",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team using ATDD finds acceptance tests are rarely updated when requirements change. The MOST likely risk is:",options:["A. Tests run too fast","B. Acceptance tests become outdated and no longer represent current requirements","C. Developers stop writing code","D. The backlog grows unmanageable"],answer:1,explanation:"Outdated acceptance tests provide false confidence — they pass but no longer test the actual required behavior."},
{id:1203,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Exploratory Testing",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team performs exploratory testing only at the end of the release. What is the PRIMARY issue?",options:["A. Exploratory testing takes too long","B. Defects found late are expensive to fix and may delay the release","C. Exploratory testing cannot find real defects","D. The tester needs more information"],answer:1,explanation:"Exploratory testing should occur throughout iterations — late discovery means expensive last-minute fixes."},
{id:1204,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"User Story Testing",difficulty:"extreme",question:"When is the BEST time to define acceptance criteria for a user story?",options:["A. After the story is implemented","B. Before the story enters the sprint during backlog refinement","C. During sprint review","D. After the first test run"],answer:1,explanation:"Defining acceptance criteria before the sprint starts ensures the team has a shared understanding before development begins."},
{id:1205,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test Automation in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"What does ROI stand for in the context of test automation investment?",options:["A. Return on Investment","B. Risk of Implementation","C. Range of Integration","D. Rate of Improvement"],answer:0,explanation:"ROI (Return on Investment) measures whether automation savings exceed the cost of building and maintaining it."},
{id:1206,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"CI/CD and Testing",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is a smoke test in CI/CD?",options:["A. A test for fire safety systems","B. A quick sanity check that verifies basic functionality after a build","C. A comprehensive regression test","D. A performance test"],answer:1,explanation:"A smoke test is a fast, basic check confirming the build is stable enough for further testing."},
{id:1207,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test-Driven Development",difficulty:"easy",question:"TDD stands for:",options:["A. Test Documentation Design","B. Test-Driven Development","C. Technical Design Directive","D. Testing During Deployment"],answer:1,explanation:"TDD stands for Test-Driven Development — tests are written before the code they verify."},
{id:1208,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"BDD",difficulty:"easy",question:"In BDD, who can typically read and understand the scenarios?",options:["A. Only developers","B. Only testers","C. Business stakeholders developers and testers","D. Only project managers"],answer:2,explanation:"BDD scenarios are written in plain language so business stakeholders, developers, and testers can all understand them."},
{id:1209,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Exploratory Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following is NOT a benefit of exploratory testing?",options:["A. Discovering unexpected behavior","B. Providing fully reproducible scripted test coverage","C. Testing complex scenarios difficult to script","D. Providing quick feedback on new features"],answer:1,explanation:"Exploratory testing is unscripted by nature — reproducibility requires documentation of what was explored."},
{id:1210,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"User Story Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"What does the T in INVEST stand for for user stories?",options:["A. Trackable","B. Testable","C. Time-boxed","D. Transparent"],answer:1,explanation:"The T in INVEST stands for Testable — each user story must have verifiable acceptance criteria."},
{id:1211,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test Automation in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a test stub in automated testing?",options:["A. A test that is not yet implemented","B. A simplified replacement for a component that returns predefined responses","C. A manually executed test","D. A test that always passes"],answer:1,explanation:"A test stub replaces a real component with a simplified version that returns controlled responses for testing."},
{id:1212,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"CI/CD and Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the difference between continuous integration and continuous delivery?",options:["A. CI is manual; CD is automated","B. CI integrates and tests code continuously; CD also automates deployment to staging or production","C. CI is for testing; CD is for documentation","D. They are the same thing"],answer:1,explanation:"CI focuses on automatic integration and testing; CD extends this to automatically deploying releasable software."},
{id:1213,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test-Driven Development",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is meant by the refactor step in TDD?",options:["A. Rewriting the test","B. Improving the code structure without changing its behavior with tests still passing","C. Adding new features","D. Removing the test after it passes"],answer:1,explanation:"Refactoring cleans up code after tests pass — improving design without changing behavior, verified by green tests."},
{id:1214,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"ATDD",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the three amigos concept in ATDD?",options:["A. Three parallel test environments","B. A meeting between a developer tester and Product Owner to define acceptance criteria","C. Three layers of automated testing","D. Three rounds of review before a story is accepted"],answer:1,explanation:"Three amigos (developer, tester, PO) meet before development to collaboratively define and agree on acceptance criteria."},
{id:1215,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"BDD",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the Gherkin language used for in BDD?",options:["A. Writing production code","B. Describing feature behavior in a structured human-readable format","C. Automating deployment scripts","D. Writing database queries"],answer:1,explanation:"Gherkin is a structured, human-readable DSL used to describe behavior in BDD feature files."},
{id:1216,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Exploratory Testing",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which of the following BEST describes a test session in exploratory testing?",options:["A. A day of formal scripted testing","B. A time-boxed focused investigation of the system with a specific charter","C. A meeting to review test cases","D. An automated test run"],answer:1,explanation:"An exploratory test session is time-boxed with a specific charter — focused investigation rather than open-ended browsing."},
{id:1217,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"User Story Testing",difficulty:"easy",question:"The V in INVEST stands for:",options:["A. Verifiable","B. Valuable","C. Visual","D. Versioned"],answer:1,explanation:"The V in INVEST stands for Valuable — the story must deliver value to the user or customer."},
{id:1218,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test Automation in Agile",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is test flakiness in automated testing?",options:["A. Tests that always fail","B. Tests that produce inconsistent results without code changes","C. Tests that run very slowly","D. Tests that require manual review"],answer:1,explanation:"Flaky tests produce inconsistent pass/fail results with no code changes, undermining CI reliability."},
{id:1219,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"CI/CD and Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is a blue-green deployment?",options:["A. A deployment with blue and green user interfaces","B. A technique using two identical environments where traffic shifts to the new version while the old one is kept on standby","C. A type of performance test","D. A Kanban column configuration"],answer:1,explanation:"Blue-green deployment maintains two identical environments, allowing instant rollback by switching traffic back."},
{id:1220,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test-Driven Development",difficulty:"hard",question:"What does baby steps mean in TDD?",options:["A. Using small screens for testing","B. Writing the smallest possible test and code increments to move forward safely","C. Hiring junior developers","D. Reducing sprint length"],answer:1,explanation:"Baby steps in TDD means progressing in tiny increments — small test, small code, small refactor — reducing risk."},
{id:1221,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"ATDD",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the purpose of example mapping in ATDD?",options:["A. To create a map of the application's pages","B. To break down user stories into concrete examples rules and questions before development","C. To document test execution results","D. To map test cases to requirements"],answer:1,explanation:"Example mapping structures conversations about user stories into examples, rules, and questions to clarify acceptance criteria."},
{id:1222,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"BDD",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following is a benefit of using BDD scenarios as executable specifications?",options:["A. They reduce the number of developers needed","B. They serve as both documentation and automated tests that verify the behavior","C. They eliminate the need for manual testing","D. They replace the product backlog"],answer:1,explanation:"BDD scenarios serve dual purpose — they document behavior in plain language AND can be automated as tests."},
{id:1223,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Exploratory Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the main difference between scripted and exploratory testing?",options:["A. Scripted testing is automated; exploratory is manual","B. Scripted follows predetermined steps; exploratory adapts dynamically based on findings","C. Exploratory is only for experienced testers","D. Scripted testing finds more defects"],answer:1,explanation:"Scripted testing follows a fixed path; exploratory testing dynamically adapts based on what the tester discovers."},
{id:1224,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"User Story Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"A user story says As a user I want to log in so that I can access my account. Which acceptance criterion is MOST appropriate?",options:["A. The login button must be blue","B. Given valid credentials when I submit login then I am redirected to my dashboard","C. The system shall use SHA-256 encryption","D. Login must take less than 5 seconds"],answer:1,explanation:"Acceptance criteria should describe observable behavior — a Given-When-Then scenario is ideal for testability."},
{id:1225,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test Automation in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a mock object in automated testing?",options:["A. A fake product demonstration","B. A test double that verifies interactions and returns configured responses","C. A physical model of the system","D. A failing test"],answer:1,explanation:"A mock object verifies that specific interactions occurred and returns configured responses, enabling isolated unit testing."},
{id:1226,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"CI/CD and Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is shift-left testing in the context of CI/CD?",options:["A. Moving the Kanban board to the left","B. Introducing testing activities earlier in the pipeline to catch defects sooner","C. Running tests only on the left environment","D. Reducing the number of test stages"],answer:1,explanation:"Shift-left in CI/CD means introducing testing as early as possible in the pipeline — even at code commit time."},
{id:1227,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test-Driven Development",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a test double in TDD?",options:["A. Running each test twice","B. An object that stands in for a real dependency during testing","C. A test that has two assertions","D. A pair of tests for positive and negative scenarios"],answer:1,explanation:"A test double is a generic term for any object used in place of a real dependency, including stubs, mocks, and fakes."},
{id:1228,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"ATDD",difficulty:"easy",question:"In ATDD, when are acceptance tests written?",options:["A. After the sprint is complete","B. Before development begins to define expected behavior","C. During the sprint review","D. Only when bugs are found"],answer:1,explanation:"ATDD acceptance tests are written before development begins to define what done looks like."},
{id:1229,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"BDD",difficulty:"easy",question:"In BDD, the Given step describes:",options:["A. The action to perform","B. The initial context or precondition","C. The expected outcome","D. The test configuration"],answer:1,explanation:"The Given step sets up the initial context or precondition for the scenario."},
{id:1230,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Exploratory Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the debrief in session-based exploratory testing?",options:["A. A penalty for testers who find no bugs","B. A structured review after the session to share findings and assess coverage","C. The start of a new test session","D. A management report"],answer:1,explanation:"The debrief is a structured conversation after an exploratory session to share findings and assess coverage achieved."},
{id:1231,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"User Story Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"What does the E in INVEST stand for for user stories?",options:["A. Executable","B. Estimable","C. Expandable","D. Essential"],answer:1,explanation:"The E in INVEST stands for Estimable — the team must be able to estimate the effort required for the story."},
{id:1232,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test Automation in Agile",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is regression testing automation MOST used for?",options:["A. Testing new features that have never been tested before","B. Quickly re-verifying that existing functionality still works after changes","C. Creating new test strategies","D. Replacing exploratory testing"],answer:1,explanation:"Regression automation quickly re-checks existing functionality after changes, preventing regressions from shipping."},
{id:1233,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"CI/CD and Testing",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does CD stand for in CI/CD?",options:["A. Code Deployment","B. Continuous Delivery or Continuous Deployment","C. Complete Documentation","D. Certified Developer"],answer:1,explanation:"CD stands for Continuous Delivery or Continuous Deployment — automating the release pipeline."},
{id:1234,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test-Driven Development",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which of the following BEST describes the green phase in TDD?",options:["A. Writing the refactored code","B. Writing the minimum code necessary to make the failing test pass","C. Running all tests and confirming they pass","D. Adding more features beyond what the test requires"],answer:1,explanation:"The green phase is writing just enough code to make the failing test pass — no more, no less."},
{id:1235,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"ATDD",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the relationship between ATDD and BDD?",options:["A. They are completely different practices with no relationship","B. BDD is a specialization of ATDD where behavior is described in natural language scenarios","C. ATDD replaces BDD in Agile projects","D. BDD is only used in non-Agile projects"],answer:1,explanation:"BDD is a variant of ATDD that uses natural language (Gherkin) scenarios to express acceptance criteria."},
{id:1236,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"BDD",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is Living Documentation in BDD?",options:["A. Documentation that is constantly rewritten","B. BDD scenarios that are always up-to-date because they are executable tests tied to the code","C. A type of Agile meeting","D. An automated deployment tool"],answer:1,explanation:"Living documentation means BDD scenarios always reflect the current behavior because they are executable tests."},
{id:1237,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Exploratory Testing",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A tester finishes an exploratory session and found no bugs. What is the MOST appropriate action?",options:["A. Report that the application is bug-free","B. Document what was explored and covered then plan a session targeting different risk areas","C. Cancel future exploratory sessions","D. Report failure to management"],answer:1,explanation:"No bugs found means the explored area has low risk — document coverage and target unexplored risk areas next."},
{id:1238,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"User Story Testing",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A user story has passed all acceptance tests but users still report usability issues. This MOST illustrates:",options:["A. The acceptance tests were wrong","B. Acceptance tests cover specified behavior but may miss non-functional usability qualities","C. The developers wrote bad code","D. The Definition of Done is too strict"],answer:1,explanation:"Acceptance tests verify functional behavior — usability and UX issues require separate exploratory and usability testing."},
{id:1239,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"Test Automation in Agile",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team's test automation coverage is 95% but they still frequently discover production bugs. The MOST likely cause is:",options:["A. 95% coverage is too high","B. High code coverage does not guarantee the right behaviors are being tested","C. The CI pipeline is too fast","D. Developers are writing too many tests"],answer:1,explanation:"Coverage metrics measure which lines are executed, not whether the right behaviors are asserted — tests can pass and still miss defects."},
{id:1240,chapter:"Agile Testing Methods Techniques and Tools",topic:"CI/CD and Testing",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team enables continuous deployment to production but skips exploratory and UAT testing. The PRIMARY risk is:",options:["A. Deployment will be too slow","B. Automated tests may not catch all behavioral and usability defects that reach real users","C. The CI pipeline will fail","D. Story points will be wasted"],answer:1,explanation:"Automated tests in pipelines cannot replace human exploratory and acceptance testing — real user scenarios may be missed."},
{id:1241,chapter:"Communicating Test Status in Agile",topic:"Test Progress in Agile",difficulty:"easy",question:"In Agile, how should test progress be communicated?",options:["A. Through a formal monthly status report","B. Continuously and transparently using visible metrics and information radiators","C. Only when testing is complete","D. Through written emails to management"],answer:1,explanation:"Agile values continuous, transparent communication of test progress through visible artifacts like Kanban boards and burn-down charts."},
{id:1242,chapter:"Communicating Test Status in Agile",topic:"Burn-Down Charts",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does a burn-down chart show in Agile?",options:["A. The number of developers on the team","B. The amount of work remaining over time in a sprint","C. The number of test cases written","D. The defect density over the project"],answer:1,explanation:"A burn-down chart shows how much work remains versus time, helping the team track sprint progress."},
{id:1243,chapter:"Communicating Test Status in Agile",topic:"Velocity",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is velocity in Agile?",options:["A. The speed of the CI pipeline","B. The average amount of work (story points) completed per sprint","C. The number of bugs fixed per sprint","D. The time to deploy a release"],answer:1,explanation:"Velocity is the average story points completed per sprint, used to forecast future capacity."},
{id:1244,chapter:"Communicating Test Status in Agile",topic:"Definition of Done",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the Definition of Done in Agile?",options:["A. A list of features to implement","B. A shared checklist of criteria that must be met before a story is considered complete","C. The acceptance criteria for individual stories","D. The release plan"],answer:1,explanation:"The Definition of Done is a shared checklist ensuring the whole team agrees on what complete means."},
{id:1245,chapter:"Communicating Test Status in Agile",topic:"Product Backlog",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the product backlog in Agile?",options:["A. A list of defects to fix","B. An ordered list of all desired work for the product","C. The sprint backlog for the current iteration","D. A record of completed features"],answer:1,explanation:"The product backlog is an ordered, living list of all desired features, enhancements, and fixes for the product."},
{id:1246,chapter:"Communicating Test Status in Agile",topic:"Sprint Backlog",difficulty:"medium",question:"What does the sprint backlog represent?",options:["A. All items in the product backlog","B. The set of items selected for the current sprint plus the plan for delivering them","C. The list of defects found in the current sprint","D. The product release plan"],answer:1,explanation:"The sprint backlog contains items selected from the product backlog for the current sprint plus the implementation plan."},
{id:1247,chapter:"Communicating Test Status in Agile",topic:"Kanban Board Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the purpose of a Kanban board in test status communication?",options:["A. To assign tasks to individual team members","B. To provide real-time visual status of work items through their workflow stages","C. To store test documentation","D. To generate automated reports"],answer:1,explanation:"A Kanban board gives instant visual status of all work items, enabling the whole team to see what is in progress and what is blocked."},
{id:1248,chapter:"Communicating Test Status in Agile",topic:"Communicating Test Results",difficulty:"medium",question:"How does a tester BEST communicate a blocker during a Daily Scrum?",options:["A. Send an email after the standup","B. Briefly state the blocking issue and request help so the Scrum Master can remove the impediment","C. Wait for the sprint review to raise issues","D. Document it in the test plan"],answer:1,explanation:"Daily Scrum is the right forum to surface blockers — the Scrum Master can then help remove impediments."},
{id:1249,chapter:"Communicating Test Status in Agile",topic:"Test Progress in Agile",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a test progress report in Agile?",options:["A. A formal document delivered at the end of the project","B. A lightweight regularly updated summary of test status coverage and risks","C. A list of all test cases written","D. The sprint retrospective notes"],answer:1,explanation:"Agile test progress reports are lightweight, frequently updated, and focused on status, coverage, and current risks."},
{id:1250,chapter:"Communicating Test Status in Agile",topic:"Burn-Down Charts",difficulty:"medium",question:"A burn-down chart shows the remaining work increasing mid-sprint. This MOST likely indicates:",options:["A. The team is ahead of schedule","B. New work was added or existing estimates were revised upward","C. The sprint is going perfectly","D. Velocity is improving"],answer:1,explanation:"Increasing burn-down indicates scope was added or work is more complex than estimated — the team should investigate."}